VALUES
(1, 22, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'as the stars of the heaven', 80, 106, 'connection', 'Celestial Imagery', 'The imagery of stars is echoed in Genesis 15:5, where God tells Abraham to count the stars to illustrate the multitude of his descendants. This connection highlights the vastness of God''s promise and reinforces the theme of faith in the unseen, encouraging believers to trust in God''s expansive plans.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 15:5", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham regarding his descendants"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'thy seed shall possess the gate of his enemies', 157, 203, 'question', 'Understanding Victory', 'What does it mean for ''thy seed'' to possess the gate of his enemies? This phrase suggests authority and victory over adversaries. How does this concept of overcoming opposition influence your understanding of spiritual battles in your life today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 17, 17, 'kjv', 'and in multiplying I will multiply thy seed', 36, 79, 'greek', 'Hebrew Multiplication', 'רָבָה (rabah, H7235) - to be or become great, numerous. This term underlines the promise of exponential increase, emphasizing God''s ability to bring about abundance from faithfulness. It reflects a core theme of God''s faithfulness in fulfilling His covenant.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7235", "description": "The Hebrew word for multiplication"}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And in thy seed shall all the nations of the earth be blessed;', 0, 62, 'connection', 'Universal Blessing Theme', 'This phrase echoes the promise found in Galatians 3:8, where Paul states that the gospel was preached beforehand to Abraham, indicating that all nations would be blessed through him. This connection highlights the continuity of God''s redemptive plan from Abraham through to Christ, emphasizing that the blessings promised to Abraham extend to all humanity.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Galatians 3:8", "description": "Paul\u2019s affirmation of the promise to Abraham and its implications for all nations."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'because thou hast obeyed my voice.', 63, 97, 'theology', 'Obedience and Blessing', 'Many scholars believe this verse underscores a key theological principle: the link between obedience to God''s commands and the blessings that follow. This theme is prevalent throughout Scripture, suggesting that faith is not merely belief but is demonstrated through actions. This obedience is what sets Abraham apart as a model of faith for believers.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the relationship between obedience and divine blessing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'in thy seed shall all the nations of the earth be blessed;', 4, 62, 'question', 'Meaning of ''Seed''', 'What does ''seed'' signify in this context, and how does it relate to both Abraham''s physical descendants and the spiritual lineage through Christ? Reflecting on this can deepen our understanding of God''s covenant promises and their fulfillment in the New Testament.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 18, 18, 'kjv', 'And in thy seed shall all the nations of the earth be blessed;', 0, 62, 'greek', 'Significance of ''seed''', 'σπέρμα (sperma, G4690) - seed, offspring, descendants. This term not only refers to physical lineage but is also used in a broader sense to denote a spiritual heritage, connecting Abraham''s descendants to the fulfillment of God''s promises through Christ.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G4690", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term ''sperma''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'returned unto his young men', 11, 38, 'connection', 'Abraham''s Leadership', 'This phrase highlights Abraham''s role as a leader and guide. It connects to Genesis 24:2-3, where Abraham instructs his servant to find a wife for Isaac, showcasing his responsibility for his family''s future. The return to his young men emphasizes the importance of community and shared journey in faith, illustrating that God''s call often involves others.', 'arrow.triangle.branch', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 24:2-3", "description": "Abraham''s leadership and guidance in family matters."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'went together to Beer–sheba', 61, 88, 'theology', 'Significance of Beer-sheba', 'Beer-sheba holds theological significance as a location of covenantal promises. Many scholars believe it represents a place of peace and divine provision, marking a new chapter in Abraham''s life after the test of faith with Isaac. This reflects God''s faithfulness in leading His people to places of rest and fulfillment.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discussion on the significance of Beer-sheba in Abraham''s life."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 19, 19, 'kjv', 'Abraham dwelt at Beer–sheba', 94, 121, 'question', 'What does dwelling signify?', 'What does it mean for Abraham to dwell at Beer-sheba after his profound experience? How does this choice reflect his understanding of God''s provision and presence in his life? Consider how dwelling might symbolize a state of rest and trust in God''s ongoing promises.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'it was told Abraham, saying, Behold, Milcah, she hath also born children unto thy brother Nahor;', 45, 141, 'connection', 'Family Lineage Significance', 'The mention of Milcah bearing children to Nahor connects to Genesis 11:29, where Nahor''s family is first introduced. This connection emphasizes the importance of family lineage in the biblical narrative, as it shows the continuity of God''s promises through generations. Tracking genealogies is a common theme in Scripture that illustrates God''s faithfulness across time.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 11:29", "description": "Introduces Nahor and his family background."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'Milcah, she hath also born children', 82, 117, 'theology', 'Role of Women in Scripture', 'This passage highlights the critical role of women in the biblical narrative. Milcah''s mention signifies the importance of female figures in the unfolding story of God''s covenant. Many scholars believe that women, often overlooked, are integral to the fulfillment of God''s promises, as their actions and decisions impact the lineage and the covenant community.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 20, 20, 'kjv', 'saying, Behold, Milcah, she hath also born children', 66, 117, 'question', 'What Does This Reveal?', 'What does the announcement of Milcah''s children reveal about God''s plans for Abraham''s family? Consider how God is not only concerned with Abraham''s immediate lineage but also the broader implications for future generations. How does this understanding affect your view of God''s promises in your life?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Huz his firstborn, and Buz his brother,', 0, 39, 'connection', 'Connecting Family Lines', 'The mention of Huz and Buz as the firstborn and brother respectively may connect to the broader narrative of genealogies in Genesis, specifically Genesis 10:22, which lists the descendants of Shem, Ham, and Japheth. Understanding these familial connections helps trace the lineage leading to significant biblical figures, illustrating God''s unfolding plan through generations.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 10:22", "description": "This verse outlines the descendants of Shem, connecting to the theme of lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Huz his firstborn, and Buz his brother,', 0, 39, 'question', 'Reflecting on Birth Order', 'What significance might there be in the mention of Huz as the firstborn? In biblical culture, the firstborn often held a special status, including rights and responsibilities. How does this understanding affect your view of family roles in Scripture and their implications for God''s promises?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Kemuel the father of Aram,', 44, 70, 'theology', 'The Role of Fathers', 'The designation of Kemuel as ''the father of Aram'' suggests a theological emphasis on the importance of fatherhood and lineage in God''s redemptive plan. Many scholars believe this highlights how familial relationships are integral to understanding God''s covenant, as seen throughout the Bible, where God often interacts with humanity through family units.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 21, 21, 'kjv', 'Kemuel the father of Aram,', 44, 70, 'greek', 'Understanding ''Father''', 'πατήρ (patēr, G3962) - father, originator. Although this is a Hebrew context, the Greek term ''patēr'' is significant in the New Testament when referring to God as Father. The relationship established here between Kemuel and Aram foreshadows the spiritual fatherhood that will be central in Christian theology.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G3962", "description": "This Strong''s number refers to the Greek word for father, relevant in understanding familial dynamics."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Chesed, and Hazo, and Pildash, and Jidlaph, and Bethuel', 4, 59, 'connection', 'Family Connections', 'The names listed here, particularly Bethuel, connect to the lineage of Abraham''s family. Bethuel is significant as he is the father of Rebekah, who becomes Isaac''s wife (Genesis 24:15). This highlights the importance of family ties in God''s covenant plan.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 24:15", "description": "Rebekah''s lineage is traced back to Bethuel."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Chesed, and Hazo, and Pildash, and Jidlaph, and Bethuel', 4, 59, 'theology', 'Significance of Names', 'Many scholars believe that names in Hebrew culture often carried significant meanings and were reflective of character traits or destinies. The names listed here may reflect the traits of the descendants, suggesting that God''s covenant extends not only through Abraham''s immediate lineage but through his extended family as well.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 22, 22, 'kjv', 'Chesed, and Hazo, and Pildash, and Jidlaph, and Bethuel', 4, 59, 'question', 'Understanding Family Legacy', 'How does recognizing these names and their connections influence your understanding of God''s unfolding plan throughout generations? What role do you believe your own family legacy plays in your spiritual journey?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And Bethuel begat Rebekah: these eight Milcah did bear to Nahor, Abraham’s brother.', 0, 83, 'connection', 'Rebekah''s Significance', 'Rebekah plays a pivotal role in God''s covenant by becoming the wife of Isaac, Abraham''s son. This connection is mirrored in Genesis 24:67, where Isaac marries Rebekah, thus continuing the lineage promised to Abraham. Additionally, her role is further emphasized in Romans 9:10-12, which discusses God''s sovereign choice in lineage, illustrating how Rebekah''s significance goes beyond mere familial ties.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 24:67", "description": "Isaac''s marriage to Rebekah continues the covenant line."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Romans 9:10-12", "description": "Discusses God''s choice concerning lineage."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And Bethuel begat Rebekah: these eight Milcah did bear to Nahor, Abraham’s brother.', 0, 83, 'theology', 'Divine Providence in Lineage', 'This verse highlights God''s providential hand in the genealogy of His chosen people. Many scholars believe that the inclusion of specific names and relationships underscores God''s intentional plan for redemption. Rebekah''s lineage is crucial as it connects to the fulfillment of God''s promise to Abraham, illustrating how God orchestrates events and relationships to achieve His divine purposes.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Wiersbe''s Expository Outlines on the Old Testament", "description": "Discusses God''s purpose in biblical genealogies."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And Bethuel begat Rebekah: these eight Milcah did bear to Nahor, Abraham’s brother.', 0, 83, 'question', 'Importance of Lineage', 'How does understanding Rebekah''s lineage influence your view of God''s plan for His people? Consider the significance of family connections in the unfolding narrative of Scripture and how they reflect God''s faithfulness through generations.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 23, 23, 'kjv', 'And Bethuel begat Rebekah: these eight Milcah did bear to Nahor, Abraham’s brother.', 0, 83, 'greek', 'Biblical Meaning of ''Begat''', 'בָּלַד (yalad, H3205) - to bear, bring forth. This term emphasizes the act of giving life and continuing a lineage, which is central to the narrative of God''s covenant people. It reflects the significance of family ties in the biblical context.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H3205", "description": "Strong''s number for ''begat'' in Hebrew."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'And his concubine, whose name was Reumah,', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Concubines in Scripture', 'The mention of Reumah as a concubine highlights the cultural practices of the time. This is similar to Genesis 30:3, where Rachel offers her maid Bilhah to Jacob. Such practices illustrate the complexities of family dynamics in ancient societies and how they affected inheritance and lineage. Understanding these relationships is crucial for grasping the broader narrative of biblical genealogy.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 30:3", "description": "Discusses Rachel''s concubine Bilhah and family dynamics."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'she bare also Tebah, and Gaham, and Thahash, and Maachah.', 42, 99, 'theology', 'Significance of Name Lists', 'Many scholars believe that genealogies serve a theological purpose in Scripture, emphasizing God’s plan through family lines. In this case, the listing of Reumah''s children underlines the continuity of Abraham''s lineage and the fulfillment of God''s promises. This suggests that all individuals, regardless of their status, play a role in God''s overarching narrative.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'whose name was Reumah,', 19, 41, 'greek', 'Name Meaning', 'Although this passage is in Hebrew, the study of names plays a crucial role in understanding character significance in Scripture. The name ''Reumah'' (H7345) means ''to be high, elevated.'' This reflects the importance placed on names in biblical texts, often conveying a deeper meaning about the individual''s role or character in God''s plan.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H7345", "description": "Strong''s number for the name Reumah."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 22, 24, 24, 'kjv', 'she bare also Tebah, and Gaham, and Thahash, and Maachah.', 42, 99, 'question', 'Understanding Lineage', 'What does the inclusion of Reumah''s children teach us about God’s view of family and heritage? How might this influence our understanding of our own family legacies and responsibilities within God''s narrative today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And Sarah was an hundred and seven and twenty years old:', 0, 56, 'connection', 'Age and Legacy', 'The mention of Sarah''s age connects to the theme of longevity and its significance in biblical narratives. For instance, Abraham lived 175 years (Genesis 25:7), and Moses lived 120 years (Deuteronomy 34:7). These ages highlight God''s provision and the importance of life stages in fulfilling divine promises. Sarah''s age marks a culmination of her journey from barrenness to motherhood, reinforcing God''s faithfulness.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 25:7", "description": "Abraham''s lifespan emphasizes the importance of age in God''s covenant."}, {"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Deuteronomy 34:7", "description": "Moses'' age illustrates the significance of life in biblical narratives."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'these were the years of the life of Sarah.', 57, 99, 'theology', 'Life as a Gift', 'This phrase suggests a theological understanding of life as a divine gift. Many scholars believe that the detailed recording of ages serves to remind readers of God''s sovereignty over life and death. Sarah''s life story reflects the journey of faith, illustrating how God fulfills His promises, which can encourage believers to trust in God''s timing.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Explores the significance of life spans in God''s plan."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And Sarah was an hundred and seven and twenty years old:', 0, 56, 'greek', 'Hebrew Term for Years', 'שָׁנָה (shanah, H8141) - year, age. This term underscores the cyclical nature of life and time in Hebrew thought. It emphasizes not just the passage of time but also the experiences and milestones that shape one''s life journey, as seen in Sarah''s narrative.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H8141", "description": "Strong''s entry for the Hebrew word for ''year''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 1, 1, 'kjv', 'And Sarah', 0, 9, 'question', 'Reflection on Legacy', 'What does Sarah''s lengthy life convey about the importance of faithfulness in our own lives? As her years culminate in a significant legacy, how can we strive to leave a lasting impact through our faith and actions?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Sarah died in Kirjath–arba', 4, 30, 'connection', 'Connection to Mourning', 'This phrase connects to John 11:35, where Jesus weeps at the death of Lazarus. Both instances reveal the deep emotional impact of death, illustrating that mourning is a vital part of human experience, even for those of faith. It emphasizes God''s empathy towards our grief.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "John 11:35", "description": "Jesus'' weeping shows His compassion and humanity in the face of death."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'the same is Hebron in the land of Canaan', 32, 72, 'theology', 'Significance of Hebron', 'Hebron, a place associated with the patriarchs, signifies God''s faithfulness to His covenant promises. Many scholars believe that this location serves as a reminder of God''s continued presence and the future inheritance of the land by Abraham''s descendants, underscoring the importance of place in biblical narratives.', 'sparkles', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'Abraham came to mourn for Sarah', 78, 109, 'question', 'Reflection on Mourning', 'What does Abraham''s act of mourning reveal about the value of relationships in our lives? How can we honor those we have lost while also trusting in God''s promises for the future?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 2, 2, 'kjv', 'and to weep for her', 111, 130, 'greek', 'Understanding ''weep''', 'κλαίω (klaio, G2805) - to weep, to cry aloud. This term indicates a deep, heartfelt expression of grief. The use of this specific word highlights the intensity of Abraham''s sorrow and the genuine nature of his love for Sarah.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2805", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'And Abraham stood up from before his dead, and spake unto the sons of Heth, saying,', 0, 83, 'connection', 'Abraham''s Mourning', 'Abraham''s act of mourning for Sarah reflects the deep emotional connections within family relationships. This can be cross-referenced with Genesis 37:34-35, where Jacob mourns for Joseph, illustrating how grief can profoundly affect individuals. The connection highlights the universal nature of mourning in human experience, emphasizing that even patriarchs like Abraham faced loss and sorrow.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 37:34-35", "description": "Jacob mourns for Joseph, showing the depth of familial bonds."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'And Abraham stood up from before his dead, and spake unto the sons of Heth, saying,', 0, 83, 'theology', 'The Role of Mourning', 'Many scholars believe that Abraham''s mourning signifies the importance of honoring those who have passed away. This act of standing up and speaking to the sons of Heth indicates a transition from grief to a practical response in securing a burial place, which underscores the theological principle of dignity in death. It suggests that acknowledging loss is essential before moving forward.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary on the Whole Bible", "description": "Discusses the significance of mourning and its role in healing."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'And Abraham stood up from before his dead, and spake unto the sons of Heth, saying,', 0, 83, 'question', 'Facing Mortality', 'What does Abraham''s decision to speak to the sons of Heth reveal about how we confront our own mortality and the loss of loved ones? How do we honor those who have passed while also engaging with our communities in practical matters such as burial and remembrance?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 3, 3, 'kjv', 'spake unto the sons of Heth', 47, 74, 'greek', 'Communicative Action', 'ἐλάλησεν (elalēsen, G2980) - to speak, to tell. This verb emphasizes the importance of communication in times of grief. Abraham’s act of speaking to the sons of Heth is significant as it shows his intention to engage with others during a vulnerable moment, highlighting that community is vital during mourning.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "G2980", "description": "Strong''s number for the Greek term meaning ''to speak''."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'I am a stranger and a sojourner with you:', 0, 41, 'connection', 'Strangers and Sojourners', 'This phrase echoes Hebrews 11:13, where the patriarchs are described as ''strangers and pilgrims on the earth.'' This connection highlights the transient nature of life on earth and the idea that believers are citizens of a heavenly kingdom. Understanding this can deepen our appreciation of the earthly journey as one that is temporary and focused on the eternal.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Hebrews 11:13", "description": "References the same concept of being a stranger on earth."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'give me a possession of a buryingplace with you,', 42, 90, 'theology', 'The Importance of Burial', 'Many scholars believe that Abraham''s request for a burial place reflects the significance of honoring the dead within a community. The act of burial is not merely about disposal but signifies respect and continuity within the family lineage. This reflects broader theological themes of death and resurrection found throughout Scripture, emphasizing the sanctity of life and death.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "Matthew Henry''s Commentary", "description": "Discusses the cultural importance of burial practices in ancient times."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'that I may bury my dead out of my sight.', 91, 131, 'question', 'Reflection on Mourning', 'What does it mean to bury the dead ''out of my sight''? How does this phrase inform our understanding of grief and the process of letting go? Consider how physical burial can symbolize emotional and spiritual release, inviting reflection on how we cope with loss in our lives.', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 4, 4, 'kjv', 'I am a stranger and a sojourner with you:', 0, 41, 'greek', 'Hebrew Insight', 'נָכְרִי (nokri, H5237) - foreigner, stranger. This term emphasizes the idea of being an outsider and highlights Abraham''s status in the land of Canaan. His identity as a stranger underscores the concept of faith and belonging to a divine promise rather than earthly possessions.', 'textformat.abc', '[{"type": "strongs", "reference": "H5237", "description": "Strong''s number for the Hebrew term used."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'And the children of Heth answered Abraham, saying unto him,', 0, 59, 'connection', 'Response to Authority', 'The response of the children of Heth to Abraham''s request can be likened to the way leaders in Israel responded to Moses in Exodus 4:29-31. Both instances show a respectful acknowledgment of a leader''s status and the importance of community in decision-making. This connection highlights the cultural norms of honor and respect prevalent in ancient Near Eastern societies.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Exodus 4:29-31", "description": "The Israelites'' response to Moses'' leadership."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'And the children of Heth answered Abraham, saying unto him,', 0, 59, 'theology', 'Covenantal Relationships', 'This passage illustrates the concept of covenants in the Old Testament, where relationships between individuals and communities were often formalized through agreements. Many scholars believe this reflects the broader biblical theme of God''s covenant with humanity, showcasing how social and spiritual obligations interweave in the community. The respect shown by the children of Heth signifies an acknowledgment of shared values and responsibilities.', 'sparkles', '[{"type": "commentary", "reference": "The New International Commentary on the Old Testament", "description": "Insights on covenantal themes in Genesis."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 5, 5, 'kjv', 'And the children of Heth answered Abraham, saying unto him,', 0, 59, 'question', 'Understanding Community Response', 'What does the willingness of the children of Heth to assist Abraham reveal about the nature of community in biblical times? In what ways can we apply their respectful and generous response to our interactions within our own communities today?', 'lightbulb', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'thou art a mighty prince among us:', 18, 52, 'connection', 'Abraham''s Status', 'This phrase highlights Abraham''s respected position among the Hittites. It echoes Genesis 12:2, where God promises to make Abraham into a great nation, indicating that his status was not just political but divinely ordained. This connection emphasizes how God''s promises manifest in the lives of His followers.', 'link', '[{"type": "crossReference", "reference": "Genesis 12:2", "description": "God''s promise to Abraham about becoming a great nation."}]'::jsonb, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'none of us shall withhold from thee his sepulchre,', 100, 150, 'theology', 'Generosity in Burial Practices', 'Many scholars believe this reflects the cultural importance of burial practices in ancient Near Eastern societies, where proper burial was crucial for honoring the dead. This passage suggests a communal responsibility towards burial, highlighting the dignity afforded to the deceased, which resonates with Christian beliefs about the sanctity of life and death.', 'person.2.fill', NULL, 'standard', true, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(1, 23, 6, 6, 'kjv', 'in the choice of our sepulchres bury thy dead;', 53, 99, 'question', 'Choosing a Burial Place', 'What does it signify for Abraham to choose a burial place among the Hittites rather than returning to his homeland? How does this decision reflect his faith in God''s promises regarding the land and his descendants?', 'questionmark.circle.fill', NULL, 'standard', false, 'v1.0', 'gpt-4o-mini');